    },
    {
      "id": "4NeDtq_kCJJSi2-vtBm_F",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -780.7183722889685,
      "y": 488.55147450606245,
      "width": 1647.0716552734375,
      "height": 45,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bDC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 854923271,
      "version": 442,
      "versionNonce": 1917376868,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775569678254,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Qualities of the system like scalability, Availability, Reliability, Fault tolerance all these things",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "Ajpg3v_s08aTcydfoxbsx",
      "originalText": "Qualities of the system like scalability, Availability, Reliability, Fault tolerance all these things",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "H_ri0lWoj2KYeULuXtjIx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1885.4231862519823,
      "y": -35.5069553947983,
      "width": 3259.869873046875,
      "height": 8010,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bDD",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1801989255,
      "version": 2466,
      "versionNonce": 1448533724,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775569678254,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "The imp part of Non Functional requirement is to\nidentify what makes this system unique, interesting\nand challenging\n1 Qus in context of CAP theorem -> is my system\n    going to prioritise availability or consistency\n\n    consistence >> availability\n    reason is one ticket should not alloted to more than\n    one user\n    as a Senior engineer we can think some part will be\n    highly available and some microservice will be highly \n    consistent\n     \n    strong consistency for booking tickets & high availability \n    for search and viewing events\n\n2 We can talk to ourselves for read and write ratio\n    here in this case read >> write  -> may be in 100 req 1 is booking like that\n\n3 We should think about how our application(site) is used, what's our query access pattern\n    what will be consistency, irregularity with which requests are hitting our system and what\n    we notice people don't book tickets to events all that much, there kind of this regular\n    even consistency. untill the event is very popular one\n\n    like in world cup final may be suddenly 10 may be 100 million of people at your front door\ntrying to get the same ticket so in the context of scaling this is an example where we wouldn't\njust write scalability but instead scalability is imp to handle surges from popular events specificallly\nand we will need to design with that in mind\n\n\nWe willl prioritise these 3\nand for now we think this is alredy handled or Out of scope we can also ask if we need to put\nsomething above and remove from top 3\nOut of scope:\n- GDPR compliance\n- fault tolerance \n- etc.  \n\n1️⃣ GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation)\nWhat it really means (in system-design thinking)\n\n“How do we handle user personal data responsibly and legally?”\n\nGDPR is not about performance or scaling.\nIt’s about data privacy + user rights.\n\n\nThinking style (like read/write ratio)\n👉 What kind of data do we store?\n\n\nName\nEmail\nPhone number\nPayment details\nBooking history\n\n👉 Who can access it?\n\n\nInternal services?\nAdmins?\nThird-party services (payment gateways, analytics)?\n\n\n👉 How long do we keep it?\nForever ❌\nUntil user deletes account ✔️\n\n\n\nExample in Ticket Booking System\nScenario\nA user books a ticket → data stored:\nUser ID\nEmail\nPhone\nEvent booked\nPayment reference\n\nGDPR-related requirements\nUser can request:\n“Delete my account”\n“Give me all my data”\n\n\nData must be:\nEncrypted at rest\nMasked in logs\nPersonal data should not be replicated everywhere blindly\n\n\n\nWhy GDPR is usually “Out of Scope” in interviews\nIt does not change core architecture\nIt adds compliance layers\nInterviewers want scalability + consistency first\n\n\nSo you say:\n\n“We assume GDPR compliance is handled by standard company policies and infra.”\nThat’s perfectly valid.\n\n2️⃣ Fault Tolerance\nWhat it really means\n\n“What happens when things break?”\n\nBecause they WILL break.\n\nThinking style (same as read/write)\n👉 Which part can fail without killing the system?\n\nSearch service\nRecommendation service\n\n\n👉 Which part must NEVER fail?\nBooking service\nPayment confirmation\n\n\n👉 What happens if DB / service / node goes down?\n\nExample in Ticket Booking System\nCase 1: Search Service fails\nUsers cannot search events\nBut existing bookings should still work\n\n👉 Acceptable ✔️\n\nCase 2: Booking Service fails during payment\nUser paid\nTicket not confirmed\n\n👉 Very bad ❌\nSo we need:\n\nRetry mechanisms\nIdempotent APIs\nTransaction logs / message queues\n\n\n\nConcrete Fault Tolerance Techniques\nProblemSolutionService crashMultiple replicasDB node failureLeader + followerNetwork issueRetries + timeoutsPartial failureCircuit breakersPayment inconsistencySaga / Two-phase logic\n\nWhy Fault Tolerance is sometimes “Out of Scope”\nBecause:\n\n\nIt increases system complexity\nRequires deep infra discussion\nInterviewers may say:\n“Assume system is fault tolerant”\nSo you acknowledge it, but don’t deep dive unless asked.\n\nHow You Should Say This in Interview (Very Important)\nCrisp & Senior Answer 💯\n\n“For this system, we prioritise:\nStrong consistency for ticket booking and high availability for search\nRead-heavy workload, where reads significantly outnumber writes\nScalability for sudden surges, especially for popular events like finals\n\n\nWe consider GDPR compliance and fault tolerance as important but out of scope for this discussion, assuming they are handled by standard organizational practices and infrastructure.”\n\n\nOne-liner Difference (Easy to Remember)\nRead/Write ratio → How system is used\nCAP → What tradeoff we choose\nScalability → Can we survive traffic spikes\nFault tolerance → Can we survive failures\nGDPR → Are we legally allowed to exist\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "The imp part of Non Functional requirement is to\nidentify what makes this system unique, interesting\nand challenging\n1 Qus in context of CAP theorem -> is my system\n    going to prioritise availability or consistency\n\n    consistence >> availability\n    reason is one ticket should not alloted to more than\n    one user\n    as a Senior engineer we can think some part will be\n    highly available and some microservice will be highly \n    consistent\n     \n    strong consistency for booking tickets & high availability \n    for search and viewing events\n\n2 We can talk to ourselves for read and write ratio\n    here in this case read >> write  -> may be in 100 req 1 is booking like that\n\n3 We should think about how our application(site) is used, what's our query access pattern\n    what will be consistency, irregularity with which requests are hitting our system and what\n    we notice people don't book tickets to events all that much, there kind of this regular\n    even consistency. untill the event is very popular one\n\n    like in world cup final may be suddenly 10 may be 100 million of people at your front door\ntrying to get the same ticket so in the context of scaling this is an example where we wouldn't\njust write scalability but instead scalability is imp to handle surges from popular events specificallly\nand we will need to design with that in mind\n\n\nWe willl prioritise these 3\nand for now we think this is alredy handled or Out of scope we can also ask if we need to put\nsomething above and remove from top 3\nOut of scope:\n- GDPR compliance\n- fault tolerance \n- etc.  \n\n1️⃣ GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation)\nWhat it really means (in system-design thinking)\n\n“How do we handle user personal data responsibly and legally?”\n\nGDPR is not about performance or scaling.\nIt’s about data privacy + user rights.\n\n\nThinking style (like read/write ratio)\n👉 What kind of data do we store?\n\n\nName\nEmail\nPhone number\nPayment details\nBooking history\n\n👉 Who can access it?\n\n\nInternal services?\nAdmins?\nThird-party services (payment gateways, analytics)?\n\n\n👉 How long do we keep it?\nForever ❌\nUntil user deletes account ✔️\n\n\n\nExample in Ticket Booking System\nScenario\nA user books a ticket → data stored:\nUser ID\nEmail\nPhone\nEvent booked\nPayment reference\n\nGDPR-related requirements\nUser can request:\n“Delete my account”\n“Give me all my data”\n\n\nData must be:\nEncrypted at rest\nMasked in logs\nPersonal data should not be replicated everywhere blindly\n\n\n\nWhy GDPR is usually “Out of Scope” in interviews\nIt does not change core architecture\nIt adds compliance layers\nInterviewers want scalability + consistency first\n\n\nSo you say:\n\n“We assume GDPR compliance is handled by standard company policies and infra.”\nThat’s perfectly valid.\n\n2️⃣ Fault Tolerance\nWhat it really means\n\n“What happens when things break?”\n\nBecause they WILL break.\n\nThinking style (same as read/write)\n👉 Which part can fail without killing the system?\n\nSearch service\nRecommendation service\n\n\n👉 Which part must NEVER fail?\nBooking service\nPayment confirmation\n\n\n👉 What happens if DB / service / node goes down?\n\nExample in Ticket Booking System\nCase 1: Search Service fails\nUsers cannot search events\nBut existing bookings should still work\n\n👉 Acceptable ✔️\n\nCase 2: Booking Service fails during payment\nUser paid\nTicket not confirmed\n\n👉 Very bad ❌\nSo we need:\n\nRetry mechanisms\nIdempotent APIs\nTransaction logs / message queues\n\n\n\nConcrete Fault Tolerance Techniques\nProblemSolutionService crashMultiple replicasDB node failureLeader + followerNetwork issueRetries + timeoutsPartial failureCircuit breakersPayment inconsistencySaga / Two-phase logic\n\nWhy Fault Tolerance is sometimes “Out of Scope”\nBecause:\n\n\nIt increases system complexity\nRequires deep infra discussion\nInterviewers may say:\n“Assume system is fault tolerant”\nSo you acknowledge it, but don’t deep dive unless asked.\n\nHow You Should Say This in Interview (Very Important)\nCrisp & Senior Answer 💯\n\n“For this system, we prioritise:\nStrong consistency for ticket booking and high availability for search\nRead-heavy workload, where reads significantly outnumber writes\nScalability for sudden surges, especially for popular events like finals\n\n\nWe consider GDPR compliance and fault tolerance as important but out of scope for this discussion, assuming they are handled by standard organizational practices and infrastructure.”\n\n\nOne-liner Difference (Easy to Remember)\nRead/Write ratio → How system is used\nCAP → What tradeoff we choose\nScalability → Can we survive traffic spikes\nFault tolerance → Can we survive failures\nGDPR → Are we legally allowed to exist\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
