    {
      "id": "kDz3DxUbXyKHRvZAK8IYU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1410.7463521667132,
      "y": 10472.472677317352,
      "width": 2177.99853515625,
      "height": 2340,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bIM1",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1591871709,
      "version": 3390,
      "versionNonce": 923108580,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775569678254,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How we will get available sheets for an event -> we will first check into database for all avaialbe\nsheets and then for sheets we will check in Redis if reserved we will filter out an sent back to client.\nwe need distributed lock due to booking service need to horizontally scaled so multiple booking\nservice will be there and all of them need this detail. \n\n\nInterview ask -> What happend if this lock goes down?\n\ni -> we would detect that this is down and we would immediately make it up that means if any of user\n    reserve that in last 10 minutes will lost their reservation and so in theory for a 10 minute window\nwe could have several users go to a payment page and try to book the same ticket because this is a postgres\nDB here and we still have the ACID properties on the write to available or booked meaning one write need\nto complete before another one could write\nwhoever end up submitting the purchase first is going to win and the other ones will get error and this is \na bad user experience. this is the conversation that we would have with the product team like is it okay\nif it is okay then that is the disaster when lock goes down.\nThen we will have small 10 minutes window where we are not going to lose our consistency guarantees but user\nare going to have bad user experience\n\n\nDeep Dive\nNon Functional Requirements ->\n\n1 Low Latency Search\n\nHow we handle low latency search -> we know our current solution is slow because we do a full table scan\nCommon solution for search problems like this is to introduce search optimize database and a very popular\none and one that recommended in our interviews is called elasticsearch.\n\nHow ElasticSearch work -> way that elasticsearch works is along with other things it builds an inverted index\n    to make searching documents by terms really quickly so we can imaging we have an event and the event has\nsome text for the name and description and may be other things that describe the event and what we are going\nto do is we are going to tokenize that string or those set of strings and create terms from them so we could\nimagine that the string might be the Philadephia Eagles are playing in a wild card match up against the\nbronckle this that and the other I guess that couldn't happen NFC versus AFC,\n\nwe turn that into Philadephia\nEagles\nplayoff\nwild card and all other terms\n\nand then we can map them in a hashmap of shorts to the documents\n\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, eventN]\n\nNow we have very quick lookup such that if somebody searches descriptoin for playoff then we can easily return\nall the events that mention playoffs, \nElasticSearch also has support for GeoSpatial queries that uses a combinatioin of quad tree and geohashing\n\nSo elastic search is good way to make these search queries as fast as possible.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How we will get available sheets for an event -> we will first check into database for all avaialbe\nsheets and then for sheets we will check in Redis if reserved we will filter out an sent back to client.\nwe need distributed lock due to booking service need to horizontally scaled so multiple booking\nservice will be there and all of them need this detail. \n\n\nInterview ask -> What happend if this lock goes down?\n\ni -> we would detect that this is down and we would immediately make it up that means if any of user\n    reserve that in last 10 minutes will lost their reservation and so in theory for a 10 minute window\nwe could have several users go to a payment page and try to book the same ticket because this is a postgres\nDB here and we still have the ACID properties on the write to available or booked meaning one write need\nto complete before another one could write\nwhoever end up submitting the purchase first is going to win and the other ones will get error and this is \na bad user experience. this is the conversation that we would have with the product team like is it okay\nif it is okay then that is the disaster when lock goes down.\nThen we will have small 10 minutes window where we are not going to lose our consistency guarantees but user\nare going to have bad user experience\n\n\nDeep Dive\nNon Functional Requirements ->\n\n1 Low Latency Search\n\nHow we handle low latency search -> we know our current solution is slow because we do a full table scan\nCommon solution for search problems like this is to introduce search optimize database and a very popular\none and one that recommended in our interviews is called elasticsearch.\n\nHow ElasticSearch work -> way that elasticsearch works is along with other things it builds an inverted index\n    to make searching documents by terms really quickly so we can imaging we have an event and the event has\nsome text for the name and description and may be other things that describe the event and what we are going\nto do is we are going to tokenize that string or those set of strings and create terms from them so we could\nimagine that the string might be the Philadephia Eagles are playing in a wild card match up against the\nbronckle this that and the other I guess that couldn't happen NFC versus AFC,\n\nwe turn that into Philadephia\nEagles\nplayoff\nwild card and all other terms\n\nand then we can map them in a hashmap of shorts to the documents\n\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, eventN]\n\nNow we have very quick lookup such that if somebody searches descriptoin for playoff then we can easily return\nall the events that mention playoffs, \nElasticSearch also has support for GeoSpatial queries that uses a combinatioin of quad tree and geohashing\n\nSo elastic search is good way to make these search queries as fast as possible.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "1cNFcPqMYDXDDMAa73kSa",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 593.3089933743814,
      "y": 15021.659235672356,
      "width": 131.99981689453125,
      "height": 20,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
