    {
      "id": "dT1vAXSBihPFl-99CuMtK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -583.8534162147271,
      "y": 6107.734741694518,
      "width": 1111,
      "height": 1225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bJc",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 577699990,
      "version": 179,
      "versionNonce": 920394972,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775569678244,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Celery is an asynchronous task queue used in backend systems (especially with Python frameworks like \nDjango or Flask) to run background jobs outside the main request-response cycle.\n\nCelery = Run heavy or slow tasks in background without blocking users\n\n🚀 Why Celery is needed\n\nIn a normal web app:\n\nA request comes → server processes → response returns\n\nBut some tasks are slow or heavy, like:\n\nSending emails 📧\nProcessing images/videos\nGenerating reports\nCalling external APIs\n\nIf you do these inside the request:\n👉 user has to wait → bad experience\n\nSo instead:\n👉 you offload these tasks to Celery\n\n⚙️ How Celery works (High Level)\n\nCelery follows a producer–consumer model:\n\nProducer (Your App / Django)\nSends a task to a queue\n\nBroker (Message Queue)\nStores tasks temporarily\n    Common brokers:\n        Redis\n        RabbitMQ\n\nWorker (Celery Worker)\nPicks tasks from queue\nExecutes them asynchronously\nResult Backend (optional)\nStores task results\n\n\nUser request → Django API\n              → send task to Celery\n              → response returned immediately ✅\n\nCelery worker → processes task in background",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Celery is an asynchronous task queue used in backend systems (especially with Python frameworks like \nDjango or Flask) to run background jobs outside the main request-response cycle.\n\nCelery = Run heavy or slow tasks in background without blocking users\n\n🚀 Why Celery is needed\n\nIn a normal web app:\n\nA request comes → server processes → response returns\n\nBut some tasks are slow or heavy, like:\n\nSending emails 📧\nProcessing images/videos\nGenerating reports\nCalling external APIs\n\nIf you do these inside the request:\n👉 user has to wait → bad experience\n\nSo instead:\n👉 you offload these tasks to Celery\n\n⚙️ How Celery works (High Level)\n\nCelery follows a producer–consumer model:\n\nProducer (Your App / Django)\nSends a task to a queue\n\nBroker (Message Queue)\nStores tasks temporarily\n    Common brokers:\n        Redis\n        RabbitMQ\n\nWorker (Celery Worker)\nPicks tasks from queue\nExecutes them asynchronously\nResult Backend (optional)\nStores task results\n\n\nUser request → Django API\n              → send task to Celery\n              → response returned immediately ✅\n\nCelery worker → processes task in background",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
